make_grid[source]

make_grid(path, gridsize_x:int=640, gridsize_y:int=480, overlap:Tuple[int, int]=(100, 100))

Creates a grid template with gridsize_x times gridsize_y cells, with overlap pixels of overlap based on geotiff file in path. Returns a gpd.GeoDataFrame with RyyCxx identifier for each geometry BUGGED and replaced with rio_windows in tile_raster

Tiler(outpath, gridsize_x:int=400, gridsize_y:int=400, overlap:Tuple[int, int]=(100, 100))

Similar functions than Â´solaris.tile.raster_tile' but with more recent dependencies. So far these only work with images that have sensible geotransform

Tiler.tile_raster[source]

Tiler.tile_raster(path_to_raster:str)

Tiles specified raster to self.gridsize_x times self.gridsize_y grid, with self.overlap pixel overlap

{% endraw %} {% raw %}

Tiler.tile_vector[source]

Tiler.tile_vector(path_to_vector:str, min_area_pct:float=0.0)

Tiles a vector data file into smaller tiles. Converts all multipolygons to a singular polygons. min_area_pct is be used to specify the minimum area for partial masks to keep. Default value 0.0 keeps all masks

{% endraw %} {% raw %}

Tiler.tile_and_rasterize_vector[source]

Tiler.tile_and_rasterize_vector(path_to_raster:str, path_to_vector:str, column:str, keep_bg_only:bool=False)

Rasterizes vectors based on tiled rasters. Requires that shapefile has numeric data in column. By default only keeps the patches that contain polygon data, by specifying keep_bg_only=True saves also masks for empty patches.

{% endraw %} {% raw %}

untile_raster[source]

untile_raster(path_to_targets:str, outfile:str, method:str='first')

Create a single raster file from a directory of predicted rasters, based on the grid generated in self.tile_raster

Grid starts from upper left, so it excludes bottom and right if full sized tiles can't be extracted.

untile_raster can be used to mosaic all patches into one.

{% raw %} 
untile_raster('example_data/tiles/rasterized_vector_tiles/', 'example_data/tiles/mosaic_first.tif', 
              method='first')
{% endraw %} {% raw %} 
with rio.open('example_data/tiles/mosaic_first.tif') as mos: mosaic = mos.read()
plt.imshow(mosaic[0])

<matplotlib.image.AxesImage at 0x7eff4aed0f10>
{% endraw %}

By specifying method as sum it's possible to collate predictions and get the most likely label for pixels

{% raw %} 
untile_raster('example_data/tiles/rasterized_vector_tiles/', 'example_data/tiles/mosaic_sum.tif',
              method='sum')
{% endraw %} {% raw %} 
with rio.open('example_data/tiles/mosaic_sum.tif') as mos: mosaic = mos.read()
